ssible the moment Europe realized that Columbus had discovered not a new route but a new world. In addition the author argues that reconstituting ambition as a virtue was a necessary precondition of the American republic. The book suggests that even in the twenty-first century, ambition has never fully lost its ties to vice and continues to exhibit a dual nature, positive or negative depending upon the ends, the means, and the individual involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAmbitionxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszEnglandxHistory. 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChristianity and culturezEnglandxHistory. 0aChristianity and culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, AmericanxHistory. 0aSocial changezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial valueszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300189841423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300189841.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles